Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was higher than forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, reported the European Community Statistics Office located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 per cent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike the United States, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the policy interest rate by saying that the decline in interest rates, with the rise in commodity prices and the fall in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation in order to stop having to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 per cent to 4.1 per cent.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off because of the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Future market shares for cereals have increased by 88 per cent and the price of soybeans has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased considerably in 2007.
This year, world oil prices rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, inflation will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3%, however, over the next 3-4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the master rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly in early December. Thus, since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Institute of Polling) has never seen such a low level of socialist support, i.e. 13 percent.
For the faithful voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, more than two-thirds (71 percent) support against the fifth (20 percent) support for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the survey, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the parliamentary threshold: their support is two percent for the entire population.
Of the faithful voters some to go to vote, the number of supporters of both parties has increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous lowest point, the proportion of those who felt that the country's economic situation was particularly serious has never been so high, it stands at 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic prospects of spring and last summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population foresees a worsening and only one tenth foresees an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 per cent of those surveyed, i.e. a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, felt that the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 per cent do not trust the Prime Minister at all and 27 per cent trust the President of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that discontent with the Prime Minister can be dealt with without change of government.
While after last October's riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the Prime Minister to remain in office, this rate is currently only 20 per cent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
On the question of the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents replied that they would certainly vote and the additional 20 per cent said that they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to organize next Sunday", only 55 per cent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 per cent additional would probably participate. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 per cent of people would say no to tuition fees in higher education, 79 per cent would say no to consultation fees and 84 per cent would say no to hospital expenses.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of the voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stays.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets located in the commercial triangle of Budaörs have maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, as opposed to the fact that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas Basket has also increased by an average of 16 percent, a value increase of well over a thousand forints appeared in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already flown" to major food stores last December, did not increase sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased well below nine thousand forked last year now cost more than ten thousand forked.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices of turkey nets, nuts and poppy have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but at Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to 139 forints only.
Competition did not decrease the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, it therefore cost only 257 forints the bottle recorded including.
However, this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of his daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 percent and 18 percent respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket and this year's cheapest basket, we see a difference of 12 percent while the difference between last year's cheapest and the most expensive of this year's basket is 21 percent.
Prices rose by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in the VAT rate had already been noted in last year's Christmas prices.
This process has perplexed trade, as hypermarkets could not clearly determine which margin to apply to products as long as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the increase in prices of the daily basket has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was higher than the value of the 2006 basket, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and prices at least increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we have seen a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumption items have increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some basic necessities, the institute of statistics has seen a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the daily basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just over 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the evidence, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have succeeded in accepting the sharp rise in prices also by multinationals.
In the commercial gold triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-storage foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning important queues were formed at the crates of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is lower in the province, many multinational companies complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumption items.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the misuse of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, and the overwork of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the Chief Medical Officer of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also save money on disinfectants
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured in a serious car accident came out of the hospital but soon after he had to return there due to an MRSA infection and since then doctors have not been able to perform a major surgery because of the bacteria in his body.
Until December 10 of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multiresistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well resistant antibiotic bacterium that will proliferate rapidly in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium may cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or septicaemia, in elderly, small-weight or weakened patients.
According to the director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily lives of hospitals.
Above all, we should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only the one or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
The SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
"These patients are isolated, the health care staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them," said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they carry MRSA, but infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling of the sample is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and in elderly homes, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases occur only if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the Chief Medical Officer of the epidemiologic center.
The European Union has strict recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be conducted to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even more rare in outpatient and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals save money on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, significant deficiencies are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhaling droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other, while in terms of epidemics, the sick should be removed from each other by at least 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many patients, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower demonstrably or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why we fight this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSAs.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) identifies as its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, who was the author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness.
The official finding concerning the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd District has been drawn up.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who has since resigned from his post, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesman of the Public Prosecutor's Office of the capital after the relative finding has been established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation which had already found that the former Commissioner had not consumed alcohol before driving.
Last Tuesday, the former chief of the police station of the 22nd district crushed a 55-year-old man who stood in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, into Kossuth Lajos Street of the 22nd district. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian passage.
(In fact, the fact that he was crossing the road outside the pedestrian crossing does not constitute an extenuating circumstance, according to the Code of the road a car that starts a turn must let the pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
As a result of this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his post and requested his retirement because, according to police communication, this accident has upset him greatly.
The investigation of this case is conducted by the Budapest Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former Commissioner cooperated from the outset with the investigating magistrates.
EUR 400 million for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements in Budapest on Friday with a total value of EUR 400 million for a credit line to support education, transport and environmental infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budget financing of transport and environment projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, a credit contract worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
The EUR 150 million credit agreement also covers the budgetary financing of education-related projects.
The EIB has approved a total of EUR 300 million for Hungary, and the remaining EUR 150 million can be used later following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of €50 million for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the Metro Line 4 project was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would discuss the possible amendment of the initial contract once Hungary finalized the details of the financing of the metro with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has provided a total of EUR 8.4 billion for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB shall grant its loans at the interest rate linked to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment fee.
Bulgaria, a paradise for the EU's real estate market
The evolution of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is focused on this Balkan country which has not been mentioned in the past.
What, or who bought in this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will soon become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
At present, in real estate, Bulgaria is unquestionably the most popular target in Eastern Europe with its ski apartments and houses by the cheap sea.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Golden Sands", the "Sunside", the former Sozopol and Nessebar but they are more and more looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to the analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap area of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, business and office surfaces promise the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on the best path to becoming one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter seasons, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors are already buying in large numbers, for example in Bansko's corner.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are looking at the same time to change their life, their way of life.
Most buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
Maltese and Cypriot investors are also present. Along the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, said Georgij Jankov, Regional Director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People who plan to settle in buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old broken houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of secondary residences (since last December Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium or long-term gains.
The price of the capital's buildings continues to rise as demand increases.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years, they have risen by 21 per cent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the six percent Hungarian
According to Gábor Fodor, Minister of the Environment and Waters, the meetings of professionals are concluded on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians coming from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap, which is supposed to define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol emission reduction period until 2012.
At the present time, strong discussions are taking place on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also noted that, for the time being, it did not wish to discuss exact figures, but was prepared to sign an agreement on the reduction of greenhouse gas emissions by 25 per cent to 40 per cent from 1990 levels until 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries commit themselves, excluding emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to be provided to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a board of 16 members, probably within the framework of the United Nations Global Environment Facility (GEF), said Piac és Profit (Market and Profit).
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Gábor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Waters, confirms the EU's ambition to maintain its role as an admiral ship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement before 2009.
The Minister explained that the EU was committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent by 2020 compared to the 1990 level, regardless of the success of the signing of the "Post-2012 Agreement", and was ready to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries were also ready to make commitments tailored to their responsibility and capacity.
Gábor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the countries signatories to the Kyoto Protocol had a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time made a commitment of 8 per cent less.
Hungary has committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 6 per cent compared to the level in the period 1985 to 1987, our country will fulfil its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The challenge is great in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the reduction commitments below the Kyoto Protocol values would not be followed immediately by a new international emission reduction system that was highlighted in the new IPCC report, the international scientific body, which won the UN Nobel Peace Prize for addressing climate change.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the Earth's average temperature by more than 2 degrees Celsius could no longer be avoided, which scientists believe would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
The British Army units report on the video-sharing site recordings made during their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan with the aim of becoming popular.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) was passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan are uploading video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC announced.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are checked at the Air Force Operations headquarters in Kandahar and then transferred to Londrès, where the compatriots load them on the Internet.
The political message is inescapable
Air Force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this route and their "chain" has been watched by over 75 thousand people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered there as "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and broadcasts videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Ministry (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission to Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they were also used to make the general public aware of the real objectives of the army's presence abroad.
The propaganda published through this channel costs virtually nothing compared to the usual recruitment ads on television, which were communicated to BBC Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, but it also inevitably carries a political message as it justifies in a special form the appropriateness of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans made a game
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos have passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, somewhat hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been posted on the Internet showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were being carried out on a real mission, but the British army has only recently packed up for the loading of these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently using the America's Army shooting game that can be downloaded for free. In this game the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers as part of a more or less real simulation.
