The forces of the mega strike gather
The unions of the League and the National Association of Workers' Councils will set up, on Friday, their strike commission, which will be responsible for coordinating the undetermined strike on Monday.
On Saturday, a general protest meeting will be held and on Monday, on the day of the final vote on the Health Funds Act, the strike will begin.
This action will certainly cause important plugs in the traffic as the railway traffic will be stopped almost completely and the employees of BKV (public transport company) will also strike until 1pm.
The League Unions will make known, Friday afternoon, the details of their Monday strike, organized with the National Association of Workers' Councils.
The strike commission of LIGA - MOSZ will also be formed, it will serve as coordinator of Monday's actions.
On Saturday, a general protest assembly will be held and, from Monday, organizations joining the strike will stop work for an indefinite period if they fail to reach an agreement with the government.
This means that the date of the end of the strike, starting from the day of the vote in Parliament on the Health Funds Act, is not defined.
If the National Assembly does not adopt the Health Funds Act, the unions will immediately withdraw the call for strike.
On the other hand, if the law is passed, strike commissions will meet and decide what action to take.
According to the National Assembly's Monday agenda, it is likely that the vote on the Health Funds Act will take place only late in the evening or even at night.
Due to the strike planned for Monday, important traffic caps are planned: the railways will stop work for an indefinite period and during the morning part of the public transport to Budapest and more than half of the Volán companies are likely to be stopped.
At the same time, at different points in the country, half the track will be blocked as well.
Many trade unions and civil organizations have joined the call for strike, and the list of them is constantly updated on the League's website.
Some organizations reported that they were on strike for an indefinite period, while others reported a temporary stoppage of work.
Until Thursday afternoon the MÁV (Hungarian Railways) and the Free Trade Union of Roadmen (VDSZSZ) failed to reach an agreement on minimum services, but, as Christmas is approaching, more and more people are taking the train.
According to current communications, public transport in Budapest will strike from the start of service until 1 p.m., Budapest airport between 7 a.m. and 9 a.m., the Industrial Electricity and Thermal Energy Unions of the League will strike for four hours, the Teachers' Union and the Teachers' Democratic Union have called for strike for 2 hours and 2 hours to 8 hours respectively.
The National Association of Physicians will strike throughout the country alternately, the Health and Social Workers' Union (EDDSZ) attached to the SZEF will make a two-hour warning strike.
The most important of the four demands, made by the League, requires that the government withdraw its proposal for health reform and submit a new concept to the social debate.
The second claim requires that the new method of calculating the pension to be introduced from next year be introduced in several steps.
The third claim seeks a guarantee, in terms of retirement before the legal age, that the functions that deserve to be transferred into the system before 2010.
The fourth reason for the action is the rejection by the Free Road Union (VDSZSZ), attached to the League Unions, of the proposal of the Ministry of Economy and Transport concerning the secondary railway lines and the expectation of another proposal.
Political Capital: Hungarian Guard increased country risk
According to the Risk Analysis Division of Political Capital, the Hungarian Guard's activity, established last August, with the support of Jobbik Magyarországért Mozambique (Movement for Better Hungary), increases, in several respects, the political risk of Hungary and the region.
In its "risk warning", society points out that, in relation to the Hungarian Guard's activity, the greatest political risk is already that "in the short term aggressive ethnic confrontations can occur as a result of the worsening ethnic tension already existing between the Gypsy and non-gypsy population of Hungary".
The research institute added that the Hungarian Guard's political strategy likely to provoke this situation is the main reason for this.
As they say, this is explained by one of the main shortcomings of Hungarian political actors: "public actors have passed the public debate on the Roma affair to representatives of radical and extreme political groupings that have based a political strategy on the dispute between the Gypsies and Hungarians".
The problem is compounded, normal dialogue becomes impossible, extremists are reinforced and aggressive conflicts are more likely to arrive, they say.
However, according to the research institute, with the increased attention of the Hungarian and international media, the Hungarian Guard's activity "has significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, in particular with regard to confidence in the country's stability and democratic maturity".
They recall that, following greater publicity for the reorganization of Hungarian radical and extreme right-wing groups since autumn 2006, many associations have been formed in Hungary since the summer of 2007 calling themselves the "national self-defence association".
"The common feature of these gatherings is that they define themselves as a civil organization when they publicly declare the preparation of their adherents for defence missions (catastrophes, national defence, defence of order), armed if necessary, moreover, by invoking the incapacity of the police, of the army, in other words of the state," they added.
They pointed out that everything was going on according to the method which, based on the resentment of the political society and the parties, seeks to disguise different political ambitions in a civil aspect.
The emphasis on civility and association is therefore only used to avoid legal traps in the registration of such associations in court, but they are also a political strategy.
