Better than we expected.
As a result of the government's 2007 debt financing and management strategy, the government planned to borrow $159.2 billion this year.
At the beginning of September, thanks to a better-than-expected change in the state budget, the Ministry reduced the planned amount to SEK 152.8 billion.
The sum consists mainly of the deficit of the state budget, which is clearly going to reach 76 billion kroner this year, instead of the 91.3 billion kroner originally planned.
Secondly, these are the maximum sources foreseen for the Czech Consolidation Agency, i.e. 13.3 billion kroons, the reserve of 10 billion for the payment of pensions, the financing of state rent securities for 43 billion kroons and the repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion kroons.
She was appearing before a court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced on Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and to deportation, her lawyer said.
The British were accused of letting students between the ages of 6 and 7 give the name of Muhammad to a teddy bear while any representation of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punishable by whipping.
This 54-year-old British teacher in the unit high school in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested on Sunday at her home and charged with assaulting Islam and sedition, under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code, following several complaints from parents of students to the Ministry of Education of the Sudan.
The story actually dates back to September, when this teacher asks her students, 6/7 years old, to choose a name for the teddy bear of the class.
"Eight names come out of the children's mouths, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed," says school director Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Mohamed is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the bear photo followed by the legend "My name is Mohamed".
The bear itself did not bear any label with this name, but the problem is simply that of the representation of the prophet considered an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons' Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said that he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that could be insulting to a religious faith, "I just regret that she asked the children to vote for a name," he said, "it is only an "innocent mistake".
Opinion shared by many of the teacher's students who describe her as "very attentive to her students" and "who never speak of religion in class".
Let's remember that the first name Mohamed is also the second most given name in Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name is often chosen by Muslim families as a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can one give it to a toy, for example?
Of course, this is a question of interpretation.
They did not reach an agreement on the future status of the province on Wednesday at the last negotiating session in Vienna.
In the end, failure.
Kosovo Serbs and Albanians completed a sixth and final discussion session on Wednesday morning in Baden, Austria, without having been able to overcome their differences on the future status of the separatist province.
"It is regrettable that the parties were not able to reach an agreement on the status," said European Ombudsman Wolfgang Ischinger at a press conference in Vienna.
Stressing that peace in the region was "at stake", his American counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
"We do not foresee violence in the immediate but we are entering a very difficult period," he added, noting that "obvious tensions exist".
End of mediation on 10 December
The Troika mediators, which brings together the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo once more on Monday.
The future of the province with 90% Albanian-speaking populations could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and the Russian Ombudsman Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko submit their report to the UN Security Council by 10 December.
The discussions in Baden, near Vienna, were the sixth and final negotiating session since the Troika was entrusted with a new mediation by the United Nations last August.
Americans and Europeans consider that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the Security Council from granting independence to Kosovo, insist on continuing negotiations beyond that deadline.
"Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution," said Botsane-Khartchenko.
Declaration of unilateral independence?
After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, Westerners believe that independence under EU supervision is the only viable solution.
Pristina stands ready to proclaim it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in its favour.
Belgrade insists on greater autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," said the President of the Kosovo Autonomous Authority, Fatmir Sejdiu, in the Baden hotel where these "last chance negotiations" were taking place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovo rebellion and future Prime Minister of the province, expressed regret.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade "belonged to a past that led to murders and deportations".
