Serbian President Boris Tadic, for his part, considered that a compromise was still possible, warning the Albanian majority in Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the independence of the province.
Belgrade says in particular to fear a "domino effect" in a region still weakened by the wars of independence of the 1990s.
"For Serbia," he said, "it does not mean that a compromise is impossible."
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision should be taken exclusively by the Security Council, where its Russian ally had a veto right.
"The Kosovo Parliament will have the last word"
"Only a solution in the Security Council is acceptable to Serbia," Serbian Prime Minister Vojislav Kostunica said.
"These negotiations lasted two years.
They must end as they have begun: in the Security Council."
To the journalists, Fatmir Sedjiu had replied that "the Kosovo Parliament will have the last word on the status", adding that any unilateral declaration of independence by the Albanians would be "in consultation" with the Westerners.
