Venus' climate could reveal the future of the Earth.
Scientists said yesterday that Venus was certainly a pleasant planet to live.
Data from the European spacecraft in orbit have shown that the planet is certainly twice as small as the Earth, contrary to what was previously thought.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
These two worlds are almost the same size, with similar orbits, although Venus is closer to the Sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago Venus could have had conditions similar to those of the Earth, and could even have been habitable.
But the greenhouse effect due to carbon dioxide, the atmospheric erosion due to solar radiation combined with slower rotation led Venus to a whole other kind of evolution.
Today the planet is deprived of water, is ravaged by hurricanes and lightning storms and has a temperature surface warm enough to melt lead.
The discoveries of Venus Express, the probe of the European Space Agency, which studied the planet for a year, offer a sad vision of the potential future of the Earth due to the catastrophic changes in the climate.
The professor of physics at the University of Oxford, Fred Taylor, one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: "We are beginning to understand why the climate of Venus is so different from that of the Earth, although the planets themselves are practically similar.
"Our new data allows us to establish a scenario according to which billions of years ago Venus would have been originally the same as Earth, perhaps even with a habitable surface."
