British bankers plead guilty to the Enron case.
The three British bankers who were to testify to their roles in relation to a fraud committed by Enron's previous financial director, Andrew Fastow, changed their statement, pleading guilty on Wednesday.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew had first declared themselves innocent of the seven charges of alleged collusive fraud in 2000, committed by Fastow in a secret financial scam to enrich themselves despite their employees.
They are expected to appear in court in January.
But during a hearing chaired by U.S. judge Ewing Werlein Jr, they all pleaded guilty to fraud.
The three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a subsidiary of the Royal Bank of Scotland's PLC group, became famous throughout Britain because of extradition proceedings that lasted two years.
In the United States, their case remains an outstanding issue for this investigation launched following the fall of Enron in 2001.
The charges imposed on them in 2002 made it clear to Fastow that he was the subject of the government's investigation into Enron's debacle.
The accusations against the bankers, nicknamed the "three of Natwest" claim to have come to Houston in 2000, to organize a fraudulent scenario with Fastow and his former right-hand man, Michael Kopper.
NatWest Greenwich invested in a subsidiary of an Enron partner controlled by Fastow, who was the director of many fraudulent scenarios, which helped him rig bankruptcy proceedings.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank had estimated its interest in the subsidiary to be zero, but in fact the three British already know its value.
A company controlled by Kopper bought the bank interest of the subsidiary for £1 million.
The bankers paid Kopper $250,000 as interest for this company.
According to the prosecution, Fastow falsely announced to Enron that the energy company was willing to pay Greenwich NatWest $20 million for its shares in the subsidiary.
But in truth these $20 million went into the pockets of British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the charges, the bankers would have won $7.3 while Fastow, Kopper and the others would have won $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to his active role in two conspiracies in Enron's debacle.
The British trio was arrested three months later.
Fastow is serving six years in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is incarcerated for three years and a month in a prison in Texarkana.
The three British were released on bail of $1 million each, forcing them to live in the United States during the trial.
Enron, formerly the seventh largest national company, in bankruptcy in December 2001 after years of accounting trickery, could no longer hide its billions of debt or even offer its phony speculations as profitable.
