He refers to the Federation of Sports' expected decision at the beginning of December, regarding Munich's bid for the 2018 Winter Games.
This preference means for us, that in the period of time that we had planned until 2028 until then, we will have no chance."
However the dream does not belong definitively to the past, said Von Beust.
The Hamburg Sports Federation (HSB) regretted Beust's statements.
From this the impression would be given that Hamburg no longer wants to apply for the Olympic Games in the next 25 years.
"It is too early to close an opportunity, burying the projects already now," said HSB President Günter Ploß on Wednesday.
An abandonment of the candidacy would also be in contradiction with the statements of the head of the Senate on the occasion of the reception in plenary of the German Federation of Higher Schools of Sport.
There, Von Beust would have qualified Hamburg's bid at the 2015 Universiades as not "a substitute" for the Hamburg Olympics.
The Federation of Higher Sports Schools had first in the past weeks named Hamburg as a candidate city.
The mayor's SPD fraction blamed the Senate for not having used this precious time in the construction of housing in Hamburg.
"The development of the Petit Grasbrook was denied by the Senate for years because it played the Olympiads card and excluded the construction of housing," said SPD delegates Carola Veit and Jan Quast.
While the SPD has always called for a plan for the Petit Grasbrook to be integrated into the Olympiads and a subsequent use of housing, the CDU would have relied exclusively on the "Event Factor".
The application for the 2012 Summer Olympic Games would have raised great enthusiasm in Hamburg.
Hamburg, however, had broken down against Leipzig.
These aren't Warhols' crates.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol's list of works.
Much of the 90 Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of the 1968 Brillo-Boxes by Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", whose former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum gave a gift in 1995 at the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as much of the other hundreds of Brillo-Boxen from "Type Stockholm", which circulate on the international art market.
The ancient history is intertwined, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curative productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the powdered soap boxes "Brillo".
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with the agreement of Warhol - presented hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exposed at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time speak today of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered law into the history of art and auctions, as the original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Warhol authorized, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached over $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum claimed, wrongly, later that about a hundred wooden boxes had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have sold them to him.
In truth, the 105 crates of Hultén were produced in Malmö only in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the curator-in-chief of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum's six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals, on the contrary, that the paint was directly applied to laminated panels, using a paint roll - moreover, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic one.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Brillo Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exposure material."
Already in July the Authentication Board of course announced, that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then there has been an inexorable silence.
The rebel soldiers of Manila abandon
In the Philippines, the rebel soldiers abandoned, the same ones who had broken into a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the President for corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not respond to any bloodshed.
The faithful soldiers in power had just before stormed the hotel with tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been in the building for hours.
About half of them stood before the courts on Wednesday because of a failed attempt at putsch in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly overshadow himself with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to monitor them, apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They entered the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The loyal troops in power closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
The National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the action of the soldiers.
"People are sick of it," Trillanes said.
"We call on people to join us."
General Danilo Lim, who was in command before the Scout Rangers' elite unit, said that other units of the army soon wanted to join the march.
The regime's critics had called for a major demonstration against the President on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
Since 2003, Manila's financial district had already been the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The insurgency broke almost 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986 there have already been at least seven attempts at putsch against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
